            <div id="id2" style="height: 86px; left: 20px; position: absolute; top: 31px; width: 957px; z-index: 1; " class="style_SkipStroke_1 shape-with-text">
              <div class="text-content graphic_textbox_layout_style_default_External_957_86" style="padding: 0px; ">
                <div class="graphic_textbox_layout_style_default">
                  <p style="padding-top: 0pt; " class="paragraph_style">Crude skew can be represented by (free hand draw, so kindly ignore few errors)<br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style_1"><br /></p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            


            <div style="height: 324px; width: 523px;  height: 324px; left: 16px; position: absolute; top: 126px; width: 523px; z-index: 1; " class="tinyText style_SkipStroke_2">
              <img src="StochasticVolatility_files/droppedImage.jpg" alt="" style="border: none; height: 325px; width: 523px; " />
            </div>
            


            <div id="id3" style="height: 628px; left: 28px; position: absolute; top: 474px; width: 942px; z-index: 1; " class="style_SkipStroke_1 shape-with-text">
              <div class="text-content graphic_textbox_layout_style_default_External_942_628" style="padding: 0px; ">
                <div class="graphic_textbox_layout_style_default">
                  <p style="padding-top: 0pt; " class="paragraph_style">Case 1: Spot / Skew correlation is positive<br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style_2">Case a: When spot decreases the skew decreases <span class="style">(Short Skew - Purple Line in the Graph)</span>. So the path which ends up below spot level has reduced volatility levels during the downward trend. <br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style_2">Case b: When spot increases, skew increases <span class="style_1">(Long skew - Black Line in the Graph)</span>. As in the case above the path above spot level has high levels of volatility during the upward trend.<br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style_3">In all this will overprice OTM calls and underprice OTM puts. <br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style_3"><br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style">Case 2: Spot / Skew correlation is negative<br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style_3">Similar analysis and it will overprice OTM Puts and underprice OTM calls. <br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style">So a stochastic volatility model will over-price a risk reversal, if the spot / skew correlation is given as positive. Similar analysis if done for negative correlation it will under-price.<br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style">Correlation parameter rho is stock and volatility correlation. When we calibrate any stochastic volatility model we force them to match the current market prices.<br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style">What if correlation on day 1 is positive and day 2 is negative. A vanilla put on lower strike will  generate a pnl of the form <span class="style_2">2 * correlation * Cross gamma term. If this lower strike is not being traded, we can never be sure that this is the true Pnl.<br /></span></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><span class="style_2"><br /></span></p>
                  <p style="padding-bottom: 0pt; " class="paragraph_style"><span class="style_2">To avoid this, in a stochastic volatility model the correlation number is not taken as simply correl(StockReturn Series, Vol Series). In theory this is the correlation between Stock &amp; Vol, but this number is too unstable and might fluctuating causing scenarios as mentioned above. It’s better to assume a functional form of this correlation so that it’s more stable. </span></p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            


            <div id="id4" style="height: 320px; left: 541px; position: absolute; top: 128px; width: 425px; z-index: 1; " class="style_SkipStroke_1 shape-with-text">
              <div class="text-content graphic_textbox_layout_style_default_External_425_320" style="padding: 0px; ">
                <div class="graphic_textbox_layout_style_default">
                  <p style="padding-top: 0pt; " class="paragraph_style">When skew increases, it simply means volatilities on lower strikes increase and higher strikes decrease, as shown in the long skew line (black) – compare with <span class="style_3">Current volatility line</span> (red)<br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style_4"><br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style">In all stochastic volatility models the spot skew correlation is a constant number. When this changes wildly then stochastic volatility hedging becomes a nightmare. <br /></p>
                </div>
              </div>
